13	THE INTRODUCTION
15	The Republic of Plato is the longest of his works with the exception
16	of the Laws and is certainly the greatest of them There are nearer
17	approaches to modern metaphysics in the Philebus and in the Sophist 
18	the Politicus or Statesman is more ideal the form and institutions
19	of the State are more clearly drawn out in the Laws as works of art 
20	the Symposium and the Protagoras are of higher excellence But no
21	other Dialogue of Plato has the same largeness of view and the same
22	perfection of style no other shows an equal knowledge of the world 
23	or contains more of those thoughts which are new as well as old and
24	not of one age only but of all Nowhere in Plato is there a deeper
25	irony or a greater wealth of humor or imagery or more dramatic power 
26	Nor in any other of his writings is the attempt made to interweave
27	life and speculation or to connect politics with philosophy The
28	Republic is the centre around which the other Dialogues may be grouped 
29	here philosophy reaches the highest point to which ancient thinkers
30	ever attained Plato among the Greeks like Bacon among the moderns 
31	was the first who conceived a method of knowledge although neither
32	of them always distinguished the bare outline or form from the substance
33	of truth and both of them had to be content with an abstraction of
34	science which was not yet realized He was the greatest metaphysical
35	genius whom the world has seen and in him more than in any other
36	ancient thinker the germs of future knowledge are contained The
37	sciences of logic and psychology which have supplied so many instruments
38	of thought to after ages are based upon the analyses of Socrates
39	and Plato The principles of definition the law of contradiction 
40	the fallacy of arguing in a circle the distinction between the essence
41	and accidents of a thing or notion between means and ends between
42	causes and conditions also the division of the mind into the rational 
43	concupiscent and irascible elements or of pleasures and desires
44	into necessary and unnecessary these and other great forms of thought
45	are all of them to be found in the Republic and were probably first
46	invented by Plato The greatest of all logical truths and the one
47	of which writers on philosophy are most apt to lose sight the difference
48	between words and things has been most strenuously insisted on by
49	him although he has not always avoided the confusion of them in his
50	own writings But he does not bind up truth in logical formulae logic
51	is still veiled in metaphysics and the science which he imagines
52	to contemplate all truth and all existence is very unlike the doctrine
53	of the syllogism which Aristotle claims to have discovered 
55	Neither must we forget that the Republic is but the third part of
56	a still larger design which was to have included an ideal history
57	of Athens as well as a political and physical philosophy The fragment
58	of the Critias has given birth to a world famous fiction second only
59	in importance to the tale of Troy and the legend of Arthur and is
60	said as a fact to have inspired some of the early navigators of the
61	sixteenth century This mythical tale of which the subject was a
62	history of the wars of the Athenians against the Island of Atlantis 
63	is supposed to be founded upon an unfinished poem of Solon to which
64	it would have stood in the same relation as the writings of the logographers
65	to the poems of Homer It would have told of a struggle for Liberty 
66	intended to represent the conflict of Persia and Hellas We may judge
67	from the noble commencement of the Timaeus from the fragment of the
68	Critias itself and from the third book of the Laws in what manner
69	Plato would have treated this high argument We can only guess why
70	the great design was abandoned perhaps because Plato became sensible
71	of some incongruity in a fictitious history or because he had lost
72	his interest in it or because advancing years forbade the completion
73	of it and we may please ourselves with the fancy that had this imaginary
74	narrative ever been finished we should have found Plato himself sympathizing
75	with the struggle for Hellenic independence singing a hymn of triumph
76	over Marathon and Salamis perhaps making the reflection of Herodotus
77	where he contemplates the growth of the Athenian empire How brave
78	a thing is freedom of speech which has made the Athenians so far
79	exceed every other state of Hellas in greatness or more probably 
80	attributing the victory to the ancient good order of Athens and to
81	the favor of Apollo and Athene 
