116	The argument of the Republic is the search after Justice the nature
117	of which is first hinted at by Cephalus the just and blameless old
118	man then discussed on the basis of proverbial morality by Socrates
119	and Polemarchus then caricatured by Thrasymachus and partially explained
120	by Socrates reduced to an abstraction by Glaucon and Adeimantus 
121	and having become invisible in the individual reappears at length
122	in the ideal State which is constructed by Socrates The first care
123	of the rulers is to be education of which an outline is drawn after
124	the old Hellenic model providing only for an improved religion and
125	morality and more simplicity in music and gymnastic a manlier strain
126	of poetry and greater harmony of the individual and the State We
127	are thus led on to the conception of a higher State in which no
128	man calls anything his own and in which there is neither marrying
129	nor giving in marriage and kings are philosophers and philosophers
130	are kings and there is another and higher education intellectual
131	as well as moral and religious of science as well as of art and
132	not of youth only but of the whole of life Such a State is hardly
133	to be realized in this world and would quickly degenerate To the
134	perfect ideal succeeds the government of the soldier and the lover
135	of honor this again declining into democracy and democracy into
136	tyranny in an imaginary but regular order having not much resemblance
137	to the actual facts When the wheel has come full circle we do not
138	begin again with a new period of human life but we have passed from
139	the best to the worst and there we end The subject is then changed
140	and the old quarrel of poetry and philosophy which had been more lightly
141	treated in the earlier books of the Republic is now resumed and fought
142	out to a conclusion Poetry is discovered to be an imitation thrice
143	removed from the truth and Homer as well as the dramatic poets 
144	having been condemned as an imitator is sent into banishment along
145	with them And the idea of the State is supplemented by the revelation
146	of a future life 
